{
  "card_id": "new_york_reversal",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "New York Reversal",
  "aliases": [
    "NY Reversal",
    "ny reversal",
    "NYR",
    "nyr"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A daily profile where the London session fails to reach a relevant higher time frame PD array, price continues into the New York AM session to reach that HTF key level, forms a change in the state of delivery (CHoCH/MSS), then reverses and delivers a sustained directional move opposite to the London/early-NY extension, completing the daily OHLC.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "During the London session (02:00–05:00 EST), price moves in one direction but does NOT reach or react at a relevant higher time frame PD array (order block, fair value gap, or liquidity level).",
    "Price continues in the same London direction into the New York AM session (08:30–12:00 EST) until it reaches the higher time frame key level that London failed to hit.",
    "At or after the HTF key level is reached, a change in the state of delivery (CHoCH/MSS) forms on the intraday chart — confirmed by a close beyond a series of same-direction candles.",
    "After the change in the state of delivery, price reverses and delivers a sustained directional move opposite to the London/early-NY extension, typically targeting low resistance liquidity (failure swings, equal highs/lows) on the other side.",
    "The resulting daily candle prints an Open-High-Low-Close (bearish) or Open-Low-High-Close (bullish) sequence, with the wick formed during the NY extension and the body/close in the reversal direction.",
    "Key manipulation times to watch for the opposing run and order block formation are 08:30 and 09:30 EST within the New York AM session.",
    "Mark the daily open as a reference; anticipate New York session price action to sweep liquidity (e.g. session lows or failure swings) before reversing.",
    "Look for a sweep followed by displacement higher (or lower) within the New York session as the reversal trigger.",
    "Identify draw-on-liquidity above (or below) such as failure swings and the daily open as the post-reversal target."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Once the HTF key level is reached in New York and a change in the state of delivery is confirmed, traders look to enter in the reversal direction using the New York open candle or the intraday order block formed at the manipulation high/low as the entry zone. Stop is placed beyond the extreme of the NY manipulation swing. Targets are low resistance liquidity clusters (failure swings, equal highs/lows, session highs/lows, previous day high/low), with partials taken at intermediate levels and a minimum 2R target required. Fits within daily profile selection and can pair with weekly profiles such as TGIF for capping the weekly range.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Misclassifying the pattern as a London Reversal when London forms a swing but never actually engages a higher time frame PD array — if no HTF level is reached in London, it is a New York Reversal, not a London Reversal.",
    "Acting on a change in the state of delivery that forms before the HTF key level is reached, which may be a false/fake CHoCH designed to run lows or highs again before the true reversal.",
    "Ignoring whether London swept a relevant HTF PD array; equal lows or equal highs created during London without reaching an HTF level indicate continuation into New York, not a London reversal setup.",
    "Neglecting CSD confirmation, leading to premature entry and being swept by false reversals.",
    "Failing to distinguish between manipulation and displacement in the New York session, missing the true reversal signal."
  ],
